    "username": "@df446",
    "clean_text": "i found these subpar, and returned them after 18 hours. major problems the noise cancellation pauses at random. not as the results of speaking or any other sound that may trigger the speak-to-chat, but the problem seems to be correlated with picking up the device that's playing the tracks, and or using the next track function on the playing device. i didn't have time to test it - that was sony's job. the \"buttons\". the buttons to activate functions like nextprevious track, volume updown, etc, are simply touch pads on the right earpiece. the problem is there's no map on the earpiece indicating where the \"touch\" zone might be for any particular function, so one ends up hunting around with one's finger. this results in erroneous commands such as next track, when one actually meant volume up, or pause, for example. simply embossing something small onto the zones where the controls are little dots, for example would give one's fingers something to map the individual functions by.",

    "clean_text": "i believe almost all android phones have aptx nowadays. it's an audio bluetooth codec to deliver the same sound quality you'd expect from wired headphones. when you buy a bluetooth headphone it's important to look for compatibility. so for the best sound quality on an android you'd generally want to look for a headset that supports aptx, for apple that's aac. now there is also aptx hd and aptx adaptive which are the better versions of aptx. i know samsungs have their own codec. so they don't support aptx hdadaptive, only aptx. but most other newer androids do have the hdadaptive codecs. like pixel, oneplus, xiaomi, sony, motorola, lg, nokia etc. long story haha but if you're not sure i'd recommend to just google around a bit.",
